title.@value: What should the medium of our final class project be?

description.@value: We should build with our collaborative skills a wiki  where there are individual pages for all students, classes, projects, etc. It would be a good project for honing coding and UX skills while also creating a legacy to carry on at DSI over the years.

When Lee-Sean was talking about his work with the Awesome Foundation in class, it got my wheels turning about a final project idea. We could spend the semester planing an online/in person campaign that raises money for incoming students. 

The grant could go to the whole class to subdivided for project expenses throughout the year or could go to a deserving student? Then next years class would have to think of a new way to add to this fund somehow? 

I think it would be a really interesting legacy to pass down to the first years. Thoughts?

I would love to whether propose an idea or vote for one medium or set of those. But I am still unsure what is this "final project" is about. Here, I am questioning the actual content of the project: 1) If it's to put together all our weekly assignments into one, I think ebook or documentary will do well. 2) But if it's to create a "community" based on our own learning from this course, website + social media + documentary + some physical stuff will be nice--almost like launching a campaign. Can anybody help me to understand which one are we talking about here?

It would be interesting if we could think of a way to bring some of the digital interaction and community building we are talking about and represent it in the physical world. Very abstract idea as of now, but I would love to hear peoples reactions.

Though this class is sub-titled Designing (Online ) Communities, the idea of "online" is diffuse. I would like us to consider grounding our community (cohort) in a physical action: A PARADE!

Parades are an anchor of social interaction that still work; it makes people smile and take notice; it's a shout-out without shouting. And what better way to introduce the SVA DSI program to New York?

A parade would allow us to practice "designing for an occasion," following the guidelines Charles and Ray Eames outlined in The India Report. Unity, Discipline, Concept

We could parade down the Highline, itself a symbol of social innovative design – the recycling of an ugly utilitarian space into a pleasant, meditative, recreational space. 

We could celebrate "design" and each of us come up with a prop that answers the question, "What made me fall in love with design?" (Check out this prop! http://www.thehighline.org/sites/files/images/Icarus,%20Photo%20by%20PAW.jpg) 

We could have prop building workshops that would deepen our DSI community.

We could video it and create a Tumblr Blog that would invite people to share their thoughts or photos on "When they fell in love with design." It could be a good way to teach future classes the concept of community building.

This is just a thought and I realize that the weather will be cool when we actually march, but the Highline does have winter parades, and I think with props and perhaps lanterns, it could be quite a show.

I realize the idea needs refining, but I am hoping we can all chime in and create something spectacular!
I have my own brilliant idea that I will share below!
A website could contain a downloadable PDF book and some video.
eBook + Physical book. Combines the best of both worlds, and easy to edit and build upon for future generations.
If this is a class on "online communities" maybe we should actually build an online community as our final project? Plus, a website is easily built upon and remixed by next year's class.

By focusing on video, we can capture a moment in time as a cohort, learn to record short-form videos as oral history, and edit together a long form video documentary as the culminating artifact of the Designing Community class.
